               <p>MR. LAW conducted the prosecution.</p>
               <p>THOMAS BAILEY ROSE. I live at <placeName id="t18240603-6-crimeloc34">St. Pancras</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18240603-6-crimeloc34" type="placeName" value="St. Pancras"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18240603-6-crimeloc34" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18240603-6-off32 t18240603-6-crimeloc34"></join>, with my father, whose name is John. On the 19th of April, in the afternoon, I saw a man coming up the steps of the house, and in five minutes after I saw him leaving the steps; he went along the front garden - I called after him once or twice; he ran, and I after him; I took him without losing sight of him. I asked if he had taken anything from the hall; he said not; but I found he had my great coat on<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182406030007"></xptr>his back; it was the prisoner. I took him to the watch-house. I had hung it up in the hall about seven minutes before; it is worth 3 l.; it was new last winter, and cost about five guineas.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18240603-6-person134">
                  HENRY 
                  SHORT
               <interp inst="t18240603-6-person134" type="surname" value="SHORT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18240603-6-person134" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18240603-6-person134" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a constable. Mr. Rose gave the prisoner into my charge with the coat - I have had it ever since.</p>
               <p>(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>The prisoner made no Defence.</p>
               <p>GUILTY. Aged 18.</p>
               <p>Of <rs id="t18240603-6-verdict35" type="verdictDescription">
